---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../data/site';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The Parent-Coach Playbook is an editorial brand for parents who coach their own kid in youth sports. Three drives. One relationship."
>
  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 md:py-24 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-12">
      <div class="md:col-span-8">
        <div class="t-label text-rust">About</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-ink font-semibold text-[2.5rem] md:text-[4.25rem] leading-[1.0] mt-4 max-w-3xl">
          A field guide for the parents who <em class="text-rust">coach their own kid</em>.
        </h1>
        <p class="font-display text-ink-soft text-xl md:text-2xl mt-8 leading-snug max-w-2xl">
          Most parent-coaches obsess over the middle of the day. The line-up card. The play call. The film from last Saturday. The relationship gets built on either side of the game.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="md:col-span-4 md:pl-8 md:border-l md:border-bone">
        <div class="aspect-square bg-paper-warm border border-bone flex items-center justify-center">
          <span class="t-label text-ink-soft">Photo placeholder</span>
        </div>
        <p class="t-label text-ink-soft mt-3" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">{SITE.imprint}</p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <div class="t-label text-rust">The thesis</div>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>The drive there sets the temperature. The game lasts two hours. The drive home decides what the next week feels like in your house.</p>
        <p>Most coverage of youth sports is about the middle. We cover all three. The bookends are where the relationship gets made or lost, and they're the part nobody writes about with any specificity.</p>
        <p>Coach the team. Keep the kid. Both jobs at once. No shortcuts.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <div class="t-label text-rust">Editorial direction</div>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>The Parent-Coach Playbook is run by {SITE.founder}, a college football coach at the University of Puget Sound and a parent who has watched two kids move through eight sports, two theater programs, and an orchestra.</p>
        <p>Cornerstone essays carry his byline. Field reporting and weekly issues are filed under PCP Editors. The publication is intentionally faceless. The work is the brand, not a personality.</p>
        <p>This is a separate business from {SITE.founder}'s work at <a href="https://coachjeffthomas.com">coachjeffthomas.com</a>. The two sites do not share an audience and do not cross-promote.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="border-b border-bone">
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <div class="t-label text-rust">What we cover</div>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>Eight sports: baseball, softball, soccer, basketball, football, hockey, lacrosse, volleyball. The framework also fits theater, band, choir, dance, and any other youth activity that has a drive there, a performance, and a drive home.</p>
        <p>Five age bands: 5–7, 8–10, 11–12, 13–14, 15+. The 9-year-old who throws to the wrong base and the 14-year-old who quits the team in the parking lot need different sentences from you in the car.</p>
        <p>One framework: The Three Drives.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container-px py-16 grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10">
      <div class="md:col-span-4">
        <div class="t-label text-rust">Imprint</div>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-8 article-body">
        <p>{SITE.imprint} publishes The Parent-Coach Playbook and the forthcoming book Coach the team. Keep the kid. (2027). The imprint exists for editorial work that takes youth coaching seriously as a craft.</p>
        <p>For tips, story leads, or partnership inquiries: <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
